readme:
Service Usage

This service allows the service consumer to update metadata and the body binary associated with an Information Record. Information record in this context represents any item of documentation that is required to be kept as a record for any given length of time. Examples of an Information Record include but are not limited to:
Case assessment, plan or notes
Interview report
Health report
Application form
Primary Correspondence
Information Record will have two main parts:
Metadata associated with the content of the record
The content of the record
Metadata will contain compliance elements (required by National Archives of Australia NAA standards) and context specific elements required by the consumer (eg. data used for searching).
Actual content of the record can be a Body Binary of any type (eg. txt, PDF, doc, xsl, jpg, bmp ).
The service also allows the service consumer to register a Hardcopy correspondence or document to the Record Keeping System.
The execution of this service is a step that will occur when:
The Visa Processing Officer returns original document(s) to client. This is not considered a new outbound correspondence but additional information for existing correspondence.
The Visa Processing Officer changes the status of the correspondence (for example from unactioned to no action required).
The Visa Processing Officer checks in a new version of the Binary File to replace the old version.
The Visa Processing Officer registers a Hardcopy Correspondence or document to the Record Keeping System

Service Behaviour

A consumer of this service provides:
Identity of the Information Record
Any data item which is to be modified by the consumer. This encompasses data from any of the following CDM Entities:
Information Record Status
Correspondence Item
Document
Related Information Records
Body Binary Content
A consumer of this service receives either:
An Enterprise Service Acknowledgement
Or
An Enterprise Error detailing why the retrieve was unsuccessful.
This service also provides the following behaviour:
The service behaviour in modifying security caveat of an Information Record is by Adding new Security Caveat to the record in addition to the existing caveat. In other words, the service will not replace or modify existing Caveats in a record
The service behaviour in modifying Access Group of an Information Record is by Granting new Access to new set of users but not revoking access from existing users.
Follows an all or nothing principal for updates. This means if any particular part of the update is unable to be performed, then nothing will be updated and the service will return an Enterprise error.
The service uses MTOM/XOP instead of SOAP with Attachments (SwA). If an endpoint requires SwA then a converter will be used after the message is delivered by ESB.
This service has been altered to use MTOM/XOP by changing the base64Binary fields to xsd:anyType so that a reference to the attachment can be sent. This is converted by ESB to a base64Binary attachment reference before it is sent to RKS. The developer can choose to either convert the link into a base64 or not convert and not validate.

Service Dependencies

This service consumer must have previously acquired a valid Correspondence Item Id or Information Record Id.

Service Composition

This service is not a composite service. i.e. it is not composed of other services within the Service Portfolio

Service Flow

Service Consumer invokes service on ESB with ModifyInformationRequest.
ESB invokes RecordKeeping.ModifyRecord() on Record Keeping interface using ModifyRecordRequest object.
Record Keeping service returns ModifyRecordResponse to ESB.
Use AF1 if ModifyRecordResponse returns with error or timeout
ESB transforms ModifyRecordResponse to ModifyInformationRecordResponse and returns response to the consumer.
Alternate Flow 1 (AF1)
If the service call was timeout, ESB should return SV201.MSG-E03 to the consumer.
ESB returns message SV201.MSG-E01 to consumer.
